Let \(F(x)=\alpha f(x)+\beta g(x)\). Then \(
F'(a)=\lim_{h\to 0}\dfrac{\alpha[f(a+h)-f(a)]+\beta[g(a+h)-g(a)]}{h}
=\alpha\lim_{h\to 0}\dfrac{f(a+h)-f(a)}{h}+\beta\lim_{h\to 0}\dfrac{g(a+h)-g(a)}{h}
=\alpha f'(a)+\beta g'(a).\)

For \(h\ne 0\), \(
\dfrac{|0+h|-|0|}{h}=\dfrac{|h|}{h}=\begin{cases}1,& h>0\\-1,& h<0\end{cases}
\). The one-sided limits differ, so the limit does not exist. Therefore \(h(x)=|x|\) is **not differentiable** at \(0\).
